  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:6-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the threatened punishment is given again at large, and that in two strophes or series of ideas, which explain the emblematical act with the pitcher. The first series, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:6-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is introduced by בּקּותי, which intimates the meaning of the pitcher; and the other, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is bound up with the breaking of the pitcher. But both series are, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", opened by the mention of the locality of the act. As ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was but an expansion of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is a literal repetition of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The valley of Benhinnom, with its places for abominable sacrifices (תּפת, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), shall in the future be called Valley of Slaughter; i.e., at the judgment on Jerusalem it will be the place where the inhabitants of Jerusalem and Judah will be slain by the enemy. There God will make void (בּקּותי, playing on בּקבּק), i.e., bring to nothing; for what is poured out comes to nothing; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 19:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There they shall fall by the sword in such numbers that their corpses shall be food for the beasts of prey (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the city of Jerusalem shall be frightfully ravaged (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 18:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). מכּתה (plural form of suffix without Jod; cf. Ew. 258, a), the wounds she has received. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is added yet another item to complete the awful picture, the terrible famine during the siege, partly taken from the words of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". That this appalling misery did actually come about during the last siege by the Chaldeans, we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Lamentations 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - The second series, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is introduced by the act of breaking the pitcher. This happens before the eyes of the elders who have accompanied Jeremiah thither: to them the explanatory word of the Lord is addressed. As the earthen pitcher, so shall Jerusalem - people and city - be broken to pieces; and that irremediably. This is implied in: as one breaks a potter's vessel, etc. (הרפה for הרפא). The next clause: and in Tophet they shall bury, etc., is omitted by the lxx as a repetition from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and is object to by Ew., Hitz., and Graf, as not being in keeping with its context. Ew. proposes to insert it before \"as one breaketh;\" but this transposition only obscures the meaning of the clause. It connects very suitably with the idea of the incurable breaking in sunder. Because the breaking up of Jerusalem and its inhabitants shall be incurable, shall be like the breaking of a pitcher dashed into countless fragments, therefore there will be lack of room in Jerusalem to bury the dead, and the unclean places of Tophet will need to be used for that purpose. With this the further thought of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " connects simply and suitably. Thus (as had been said at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") will I do unto this place and its inhabitants, ולתת, and that to make the city as Tophet, i.e., not \"a mass of sherds and rubbish, as Tophet now is\" (Graf); for neither was Tophet then a rubbish-heap, nor did it so become by the breaking of the pitcher. But Josiah had turned all the place of Tophet in the valley of Benhinnom into an unclean region (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). All Jerusalem shall become an unclean place like Tophet. This is put in so many words in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
